Why should you use propriatary connector instead of using an industry standard? That is like asking "why doesn't Samsung use Apples Lightning instead of USB?" The big car companies already decided in 2011 that their electric cars will use CCS. It is used on all cars in Europe and North America by more or less all companies. And in Europe even Tesla switched to CCS: The Model 3 was introduced with CCS from the beginning here, so it actually cannot charge at the "old" Superchargers in Europe. But all SCs here were modified here  so that they have CCS now. That means, that at least in theory all other cars could charge at Tesla's SCs in Europe. But Tesla doesn't allow it and don't offer an option for non-Teslas.

I think its a shame that german auto-makers took so long to really invest in the electric market.
They are a very powerful group in Germany and always got whatever they wanted from politicians, so instead of investing long term into electric cars, they went for short term profits with their combustion engines and now they struggle to keep up.

They can still build good cars, but the car of tomorrow will need more.
Software is now a huge part of a car, AI, self-driving, charging infrastructure and that's the stuff that German companies don't have much experience with, so now they need to catch up to the competition if they don't want to lose their standing in the market.

And I think many of them still haven't gotten the message. Now during Corona when the government debated a stimulus package, the auto-lobby tried to sneak subsidies for massive polluters in there, on a European level regulations are always watered down by the powerful lobby sneaking in exceptions so they can continue selling their dirty cars.
This may make financial sense in the short term, but in the long term, it might mean that Audi, BMW, Porsche, Mercedes, Volkswagen, and other German manufacturers might lose their market share when American and Chinese brands beat them in the transition to e-mobility.

But if the competition between all these really starts to take off, I think we will quickly see massive development and improvement.
Range, speeds, lifetime mileage, charge time, and the overall cost will soon be below the current level of combustion engine cars.

Ranges of over 1000km might easily be a reality by 2030. Speeds are already artificially limited for safety reasons. Lifetime mileage will be higher because the less complicated mechanics have way less wear over time.
Quick-charging is making huge strides every year, but they're also concepts of "gas stations" where you just drive over a vent that will take out the empty battery and attach a new one, that would making re-charging quicker than filling up a gas tank.
And the raw material and manufacturing cost of electric cars is just lower than that of CE cars, the maintenance costs are also lower, so as soon as manufacturing is as optimized and streamlines as the processes for CE cars, there are no reasons why electric cars shouldn't be cheaper than what we have now.

There are two things you didn't mention. One is reliability, Tesla has been dealing with reliability issues recently. Charging issues on the Tesla Model X, non-functioning door handles on some Model S cars, and we all know about Model 3 scratches and scuffs from the factory.  Porsche has been ranked as the second most reliable car manufacturer by J.D. Power second only to Lexus. The second is, it's a Porsche. There are technical advantages the Porsche Taycan has over Tesla, such as charging times and track performance; but then there is the Porsche tax. That offers uncompromising performance, quality, reliability, and, depending on the model, luxury. In this case, that tax is $80,000. For that extra money, you get some technical advantages, and then the brand, reliability, and performance. Taycan is Porsche's take on an electric car, its the pinnacle of German engineering, it does everything the other cars do but it (usually) does it better, and the price reflects that. "currently tesla is the only one that can use Tesla chargers"
Yes, because they made their own system. There is NO other car company that has its own chargers. Only Tesla.

"and that is by choice they left their patents open so other car manufacturers can use them as well"
That is not wrong, but you ignore history here. The Chademo standard was introduced in 2010, all asian companies worked with that, and it is still the standard in East Asia. CCS was defined as an standard in 2010. At the beginning of 2011, General Motors, Ford, Daimler, BMW and Volkswagen decided and announeced, that their future EVs will use CCS. The Model S was introduced in 2012! So why should other car companies use a system, that was made by one company, when they already decided to support a general standard, that is accepted by the entire industry and in germany even required by law (when you build a DC charging station in Germany, it is required to have CCS, additional others are allowed)?

Tesla is what Apple is in Mobile phones, at least since a few years ago: All smartphone companies used the industrial standard "Mini-USB" for the devices - only the iPhone uses the Apple-invention Lightning. All car companies uses the industrial standard CCS for their EVs - only Tesla uses its own standard "supercharger".

" but instead everyone wants to make their own"
Bullshit. That is just wrong. There is no Porsche-charging standard, no Audi-charging standard, no Ford charging standard, no Jaguar charging standard, no Honda charging standard, no Hyundai charging stdandard, no Volvo charging standard, no Renaul charging-standard . They use CCS (or chademo in Japan and Korea) ! But there is the Tesla charging standard.

"Tesla has the best and largest charge station network"
In Europe there are 488 supercharger stations and 603 CCS stations with more than 100 kW. There are even 6487 CCS stations in general, but most of them offers only 50 kW. Chademo is dying out, Nissan is the only one who sells the Leaf in Europe still with Chademo and nobody knows why. And as I said, even Tesla switched to that CCS standard in Europe instead of their own system.

I know the situation is different in the USA and as a customer the Tesla network obvipusly is still a big advantage. But it is still bullshit to claim, that "everyone wants to make their own". Instead all other car companies use charging systems, that where defined and standarized before the Model S was even on the market.

When talking about electric car charging, the kw rating is not the best metric. Different cars get different range from the same battery. Instead, you should look at the mph or km/h charge rate. Tesla's drive train is still the most efficient of any long range EV. Napkin math with numbers from Wikipedia:


The Model S gets up to 370 miles of range on a 100 kWh battery, resulting in 3.7 miles/kWh. Combined with a peak charge rate of 200kW, that's a peak effective charge rate of 740 mph.


The Taycan gets up to 270 miles of range on a 93.4 kWh battery, resulting in ~2.9 miles/kWh. Combined with a peak charge rate of 270kW, that's a peak effective charge rate of ~780 mph.


So, slightly higher than the Tesla, but not as much as the raw charge rate would make it sound.

Good luck fixing it when it breaks. People buy cars for the absolutely wrong reasons... you can always tell an amateur car buyer because they are swayed by based on pompous looks, outward appearance, speed, gimmicks, tech specs, etc. All of those are total bullshit.

Once you really own a car/cars for years, you know what really matters are these: mpg, low price, swiss watch reliability, clearances to get your tools in, user servicability (can you take the engine out yourself, fix it, and put it back in?), minimalist simple design that is straightforward to understand. If you can't fix it yourself when it breaks, don't buy it! If you open the front hood (you did open the hood, right, before you bought it) - if you see the engine is packed in there like spam in a can with no space to get any tool in there edge wise - DON'T BUY IT! If it is a front wheel drive car, DON'T BUY IT!. If you can't get the Factory Service Manual for it which is several encyclopedia volumes thick... (not a Chiltons skinny book you find in an Advance Auto Parts on the shelf), don't buy it.

Your first question of any car from anyone you are buying it from - "Is this a front wheel drive car?" If they say YES, your answer should always be... sorry... not interested. If you don't know why, then you have never tried to work on or fix a car.


In the case of all Porsches, they are rear wheel drive, but the wrong kind - they are rear wheel drive because the engine is jammed in there in the rear like sardines in a can. If it's anything like a Volkswagen Bug, and it is (just a squashed flat bug), you have to unbolt and lift the entire body of the car up and off the floor pan to get the engine out. Which is completely, absolutely insane. Which means as far as buying a Porsche is concerned, hell no.

On the performance statistics, the headline numbers are not necessarily relevant in real-world driving. Far more important for track time (which is all about cornering, braking and putting power down on the exits) than 0-60 sprints is the way the power is put down through the wheels, and Porsche know how to build a race hybrid car and race it at Le Mans, so that technology will have trickled (excuse the pun) down. Also for us Europeans, our roads are a lot less smooth than America and the Nurburgring is a very bumpy and technical circuit... so this car will be an incredible drive on European roads.

What I'm really curious about is the real-world range that you get from a Taycan if you drive it like a petrol 911. Will the range be destroyed by hard driving? I suspect this is where Porsche will have put a lot of focus, since a Porsche that can only be driven like a Porsche for 50 miles, would be pretty pointless. That will be the real comparison between these two cars. And Tesla, to be fair, was never designed to win that race.

The position of the calipers can be dictated by a number of factors, - cooling, weight distribution, suspension design, etc.  Yes, - engineers of high performance cars have in the past positioned the calipers within the wheelbase for optimal weight distribution.  In the case of the Taycan, (with a heavy battery already low and between the axles) there was probably less to gain through that position and more to be gained through improved cooling by placing them outside the wheelbase, front and rear. The Taycan does actually have a supercharger network. Its called the Electrify America Supercharger Network. You can already drive coast to coast using the network. They are more powerful than Tesla's SC as they have chargers up to 350kW, even though no car can take that much just yet.


The electrify America SC network is for all non-tesla EV's that us the CCS fast charging standard. Tesla has their own standard. Tesla's SC network is way easier than Electrify Americas as there are no screens, you just plug in, the super charger recognizes the Tesla, and everything is paid for through the charger and the car itself. As for Electrify America's, you have to use a touch screen (which people said they have been having problems with) and swipe your credit/debit card to start charging.
They basically can utilize all charge points including Tesla super chargers and Electrify America chargers.
@Jeremy Lang your right.  The CCS adapter is now available in the US.  Now all Tesla's can use the EA super charger network. That really puts Tesla in a unique position.

In the future battery charging time could be eliminated if there was a way to swap the battery quickly - Imagine there were 3 standardized types of batteries for vehicles 50kW, 75kW and 100kW. You purchase the vehicle but not the battery - you lease it so in theory you only own the car and the energy stored in the battery but not the battery pack itself - this could reduce the price of electric car significantly! - You approach designated place on service station where automated robot removes your drained battery and replaces it with already charged battery, tested and certified for a minimum distance/capacity.

I'm slightly disappointed with the comparison (and with the Taycan). Some facts are either the repetition of questionable marketing statements or not completely true.
- the model s never achieved 0-100 in 2.4. A german car magazine tested it with 2.7 s. They are no tests with the Porsche yet.
- Peak charging rate is just a number. How long can the car charge with this charging rate? More important: miles or km charged per time. Tesla will win this for sure, the energy consumption of the Taycan is just ridiculous (19 vs 27 kWh per 100 km)
- The Tesla autopilot is an over-glorified driving assistant, not a pilot. I'm sure that there will be driving assistants for the Porsche too, maybe not as good as Tesla's system.
- There will be a RWD base model of the Taycan, so starting price comparison is a bit off

Just before I start, I am a car enthusiast way more than a tech fan. Okay so first thing, nobody is buying a Taycan to take to the track. 2500kg is all I have to say for everyone who has ever considered buying a track car to be immediately uninterested. This car is only going to see public roads. Even so, the driving dynamics are still very important for back roads, canyons, etc. I don't love or hate Tesla because their brand has very mixed results. I love Elon Musk but I have to say sitting in a Tesla is very unimpressive for a ¬£80,000 car. Materials aren't great and the build quality isn't good at all. I'm also not a fan of Tesla's infotainment system. I'm sure Porsche will have the advantage in all these areas. The Taycans infotainment system looks pretty much the same as the Panamera and I found the Panamera's system much easier to use than the Tesla's. I would say I agree that the rear seat on the Taycan looks cramped but it's very hard to tell just from a first glance. But at the end of the day, I don't think these cars are actually direct competitors to eachother. I think car people who like electric cars will buy the Porsche and everyone else who likes electric cars will buy the Tesla's. Tesla has kind of become a trigger word for electric cars and so I feel like people who don't care much about cars would prefer to have a Tesla. Even if it's a model 3 or a model X. To me, the Taycan fits between the Model S and the Roadster, even though it's not as fast in a straight line. The other thing about Tesla is that they basically just make electric dragsters rather than Porsche who care about handling. You wouldn't compare a Dodge Demon and a new Ford GT because they both fulfill different things. Just in the same way, you shouldn't really be comparing the Tesla model S to the Taycan. And you wouldn't compare the Tesla's to the Rimac C2. No matter what electric car comes out, it will always be compared to the Tesla's in some way because they get the most sales. But the only reason for that is that they're making cars for the masses rather than mostly for people who care about driving. And that's not a bad thing either, it's just a different thing. (Also side note, even though I think electric cars and electric motors especially are very good, they're probably not the future. Creating batteries is so bad for the environment and the bigger they get the more damage they do. Plus, batteries will slowly become worse and worse until the point where they're not really useable anymore. And then getting rid of batteries is already a huge issue. Batteries in electric cars will struggle to ever last more than 10 years. I understand that there's a long way to go for electric powertrains but at the moment I just can't see it being any better than the best petrol cars, other than the fact they use no fossil fuels if we use renewal energy sources to charge the cars. HYDROGEN POWER PLEASE!)

I ordered my P100D with the 19‚Äù wheels instead of the 21‚Äù and it‚Äôs been great. Electric cars have a completely different problem than ICE cars because they have little to no drivetrain noise, that means things like road noise become much more prevalent. This will be true in the Porsche just like it‚Äôs true in every other electric car. What Tesla (and I‚Äôm sure Porsche) will do is use foam in the wheels to help absorb road noise. It‚Äôs an extra $100 per wheel when you change your tires, but it makes a huge difference in the noise levels. My point still stands that the extended track performance is a cool feature, but not a practical selling point. The real point I‚Äôm trying to make is that these cars should be in the same market segment, but Porsche has added another car onto the price tag for a nominally improved feature set and a few steps back from the S when it comes to things like range. It looks like a great car, but it doesn‚Äôt seem like you‚Äôre getting anywhere close to your moneys worth in this case.

Tesla is an amazing product but the Porsche is made to a different ethos. They're not interested in a ludicrous mode that drains the battery & a Porsche owner wants a higher interior quality. The Porsche is made to be used on the autobahn where high speed driving over many miles is the norm. Expect after market e-tuners to do silly things with it but for the moment it's about manageable power. Traffic Jam assist with steering assist is part of InnoDrive which is their competitor to autopilot. This isn't a full self driving solution even if sister company Audi has the technology. Their reasoning is that Porsche make cars to be driven & instead InnoDrive optimises the response from the drive train, steering and suspension based on topographical data about the road you're on with a 1.8 mile prediction radius. The idea is to make you look like a better driver but not to take control. Again the Porsche has a different ethos. It's not the same as the Tesla. That doesn't diminish the Tesla at all because it's a brilliant car & they've shown everyone how to do a great electric car. Porsche knows their buyers won't care about the raw specs so much as usable performance, luxury & charging speed.

Let us not forget the fact that Porsche is most likely to come out ahead on quality, especially in terms of interior. Most likely one of the reasons it is so expensive. It looks absolutely amazing on the inside, and I do like the lightbar on the outside (heavily inspired from its sister company, Audi, as well as Panamera models from before), and if it is anything close to the Panamera in terms of interior quality, or above.. it will completely smash the Tesla. That interior will most likely also make it more comfortable on longer drives, considering the seats should be a lot more comfortable (if you choose not to go for hardcore racing seats of course).¬†It should also be better to drive for those that want a car with good driving dynamics over the A to B in a comfortable way style of driving, especially seeing how focused they have been on making it good around a track, and giving it 2 gears. 2 gears should probably make it reach its top speed faster as well? Not seen any statistics on this.. not that it matters much for most people, as they will never drive it up to that speed anyway on a normal road.

I would not call the Taycan a sedan.. it is more like a 4-door coupe. The backseat passengers will suffer in the Taycan... The Model S has more space on the inside, a better trunk solution for those in need of that, better OTA updates (pretty sure Porsche follows the Audi E-Tron here, in being ok.. but not excellent at this point), and it has better range. It might not beat the Porsche on the track.. but it is faster off the line, and a LOT cheaper. Based on this, I am pretty sure that the Tesla will continue to be chosen over the Porsche by many people, but for those few who wants a good drivers car with excellent interior quality.. the Porsche is the way to go, if you have the money for it.

The reason why the Taycan uses an 800 volt system is that there's an inverse relationship between voltage and current. They increased the voltage and decreased the current, meaning there's less heat, therefore a lighter wiring loom and better heat management in the overall system. This means you can launch the Taycan many more times before it overheats compared to a Tesla, which needs to cool down after a few launches to cool the battery pack for peak performance. Because of this effect, the Taycan can be taken on a track and achieve peak performance through the entire lap, whereas the Tesla will overheat and lose power. That's the biggest difference between them that I can see. They're both great cars anyway and were clearly designed with two different markets in mind.

Something that is often forgotten is that people buy Tesla products for their environmental efficiency and responsibility, or for their tech/engineering; they don't often buy them for performance. If I were looking for performance, I would skip right over the Tesla because it can't perform well beyond 10 seconds in a straight line; I would take a Porsche 911 any day for its track longevity and cornering ability. However, Audi (E-Tron) has a product that is environmentally responsible, high tech, and practical; this is what people were looking for back in 2012 when Tesla was just getting started. The performance aspect of electric cars is a niche, which Tesla and Porsche can battle and bicker over all day long. However, Tesla and Audi E-Tron, when it gains more traction in the car industry, will be the 2 top competitors in the electric car market. Tesla has a basically proven lineup now, and Audi is taking its already well-proven model lineup and electrifying it.

Important stats not mentioned in the video about charging!¬†
1. The Model S may charge at a 20% lower power rate, but it's more than 20% more efficient in power usage. You end up with both cars gaining the same Miles Per Hour charged, or even the S coming out ahead. It's really all about MPH. Not kWh.¬†
2. The 280 mile range estimate is the WLTP rating, and CITY driving. You get fewer miles on the highway, and fewer in the EPA rating which is what Tesla advertises. Factoring in both highway usage and the EPA rating, the true range is around 210 miles vs Tesla's 345. We'll of course have to wait for official numbers but it should be very close to this number.¬†

This cycle of monopolisation will end up in EVs not being as powerful as they could be if there were more EV businesses and more competition for Tesla to compete against.
